                       SAVING TIME WITH PARAGRAPH STYLES
                                       
   
   
   Many Word users-even those who have worked with the program for some
   time-don't take advantage of all its style capabilities. This is
   unfortunate, because styles are one of the most powerful and
   timesaving Word features. Of course, Word will apply styles to certain
   document elements without your help. For instance, when you create a
   footer, Word automatically applies the Footer style. And you can set
   AutoFormat to apply styles to items like headings. But understanding
   styles-and using them to get the results you want-will make your work
   easier and your documents better looking.
   
   Last month, we discussed how Word allows you to apply a character
   style to format selected text within a paragraph. However, while
   character styles can be very handy in certain situations, most of your
   document formatting is governed by paragraph styles. In order to
   understand how paragraph styles affect formatting (and the role they
   play in the construction of certain document elements, such as
   numbered headings, outlines, and tables of contents), we're launching
   a series of articles covering various aspects of Word's style feature.
   We'll ease into the subject this month by introducing some basic style
   concepts. To keep our discussion less cumbersome, we'll use the term
   style (rather than paragraph style) in most references.
   
What is a style?

   
   
   A style is a simply a group of instructions for formatting a
   paragraph. Every template has a set of styles, and when you create a
   new document based on a particular template, the document inherits
   that set of styles. These inherited styles provide a starting point
   for your document formatting, but you can modify the document's
   styles-or create new ones-if you want.
   
   You can also modify a template's styles, so that subsequent documents
   you create using the template will inherit the altered set of styles.
   In fact, this capability is one of the most important facets of using
   templates to generate different types of documents.
   
   A style's instructions specify various kinds of formatting. Table A
   summarizes the settings that can be included in a style definition.
   Note that although a style definition can include both character and
   paragraph formatting, you can apply the style only to complete
   paragraphs. In other words, you can't format part of a paragraph with
   one style and the rest of the paragraph with a different style. (You
   can, however, apply a character style-consisting solely of character
   formatting-to a portion of text within a paragraph.)
   
